      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "CFD solver must have documented verification test suite and version control consistent with MRL 2 requirements.",
      "rationale": "ANSYS Fluent 2022 R2 was used with documented release notes, regression test suite, and ISO 9001-certified development process. Version control and change logs reviewed; all MRL 2 SQA requirements satisfied."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Solver must demonstrate correct implementation of governing equations through benchmark test problems at MRL 2.",
      "rationale": "Standard lid-driven cavity and pipe flow benchmarks confirm correct Navier-Stokes implementation. Solver convergence behavior matches published analytical solutions within expected numerical tolerances for laminar and turbulent regimes."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Grid convergence study must demonstrate discretization error below 5% for hemolysis index QoI, with Richardson extrapolation applied across at least three systematically refined meshes.",
      "rationale": "A mesh sensitivity study was performed using two mesh densities (4.2M and 8.7M elements). Results showed less than 8% variation in predicted hemolysis index between mesh levels, which is considered acceptable given the complexity of the rotating geometry and the relative nature of the hemolysis comparison. Engineering judgment supports that the mesh is sufficiently refined for identifying worst-case operating conditions, even though a formal three-level Richardson extrapolation was not completed due to computational resource constraints."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental test conditions used for validation must be documented and traceable to the COU operating envelope.",
      "rationale": "FDA benchmark experimental data collected at flow rates of 2.5, 5.0, and 7.0 L/min with rotational speeds of 2500 and 3500 RPM. Test conditions are fully documented in Morrison et al. (2016) and span the COU operating envelope. Temperature, hematocrit, and fluid properties are specified and traceable."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Predicted hemolysis index must agree with experimental measurements within ±15% across all validation operating points.",
      "rationale": "CFD-predicted normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) compared against experimental measurements across 5 operating conditions. Mean absolute error of 11.3% observed; all individual comparisons within the ±15% acceptance band. Systematic over-prediction at high shear conditions noted but within tolerance."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The QoI used in validation (NIH, shear stress distribution) must be directly linked to the COU decision metric (relative hemolysis index RH).",
      "rationale": "Normalized index of hemolysis is the primary validation QoI and maps directly to the relative hemolysis index acceptance criterion RH < 1. Shear stress distribution provides secondary mechanistic insight. Both QoIs are directly relevant to the COU decision."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation activities must use geometry, boundary conditions, and fluid properties representative of the CPB COU.",
      "rationale": "Validation performed on the FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry, which is the same platform as the COU device. Bovine blood analog fluid properties used in both CFD and experiment. Operating conditions span the clinical CPB flow-speed envelope. Validation activities are directly applicable to the COU."
    },
    {
